1
00:00:00,050 --> 00:00:06,442
You're listening to: Cryptographic Bill of Materials (CBOM): Step 1 of PQC Migration.

2
00:00:06,442 --> 00:00:09,495
You can't migrate cryptography you can't see.

3
00:00:09,495 --> 00:00:22,019
A practical guide to building a Cryptographic Bill of Materials — what to inventory, how to find hidden crypto, how to score by data lifetime, and how the CBOM becomes your post-quantum migration plan.

4
00:00:22,019 --> 00:00:23,064
Let's get started.

5
00:00:23,064 --> 00:00:32,548
Every serious post-quantum migration plan starts with the same unglamorous step, and almost everyone wants to skip it: find all your cryptography first.

6
00:00:32,548 --> 00:00:45,108
Not the crypto you think you use — the crypto you actually use, including the dependency three levels down that pins an RSA key, the legacy service nobody owns, and the TLS config you've never looked at.

7
00:00:45,108 --> 00:00:50,661
That inventory has a name now: a Cryptographic Bill of Materials (CBOM).

8
00:00:50,661 --> 00:00:58,341
Building one is genuinely the highest-leverage thing you can do in 2026, because every later decision depends on it.

9
00:00:58,341 --> 00:01:00,072
This is the practical how-to.

10
00:01:00,072 --> 00:01:05,168
It's the concrete first move behind the PQC deadlines and the migration guide.

11
00:01:05,168 --> 00:01:08,197
Now, let's talk about Why a CBOM, and why now.

12
00:01:08,197 --> 00:01:13,774
The logic is simple: you cannot protect, prioritize, or replace what you can't see.

13
00:01:13,774 --> 00:01:25,961
NIST, the NCSC, and every enterprise migration framework converge on inventory-first for a reason — the alternative is migrating blind and discovering the RSA you missed during an incident.

14
00:01:25,961 --> 00:01:39,290
A CBOM is to cryptography what an SBOM (Software Bill of Materials) is to dependencies: a structured, maintained record of every cryptographic asset, where it's used, and its risk.

15
00:01:39,290 --> 00:01:49,867
The "harvest now, decrypt later" threat makes it urgent — data being captured today is already on the clock, and you can't triage it without knowing where it lives.

16
00:01:49,867 --> 00:01:51,838
Moving on to What goes in a CBOM.

17
00:01:51,838 --> 00:01:56,442
For each cryptographic usage, capture enough to make a migration decision:

18
00:01:56,442 --> 00:01:57,956
Field, Why it matters.

19
00:01:57,956 --> 00:02:04,699
Asset / location, Service, endpoint, library, or file where crypto is used.

20
00:02:04,699 --> 00:02:15,949
Algorithm & key size, RSA-2048, ECC P-256, AES-256… — what needs replacing vs what's fine.

21
00:02:15,949 --> 00:02:24,795
Purpose, Key exchange, signature, or data-at-rest encryption (determines ML-KEM vs ML-DSA vs nothing).

22
00:02:24,795 --> 00:02:31,514
Data confidentiality lifetime, How long the protected data must stay secret — the priority driver.

23
00:02:31,514 --> 00:02:33,641
Owner, Who can actually change it.

24
00:02:33,641 --> 00:02:37,776
Crypto-agility, Is the algorithm swappable, or hard-coded?.

25
00:02:37,776 --> 00:02:44,122
That fourth row — data lifetime — is the one most inventories forget and the most important.

26
00:02:44,122 --> 00:02:54,375
A session token that's worthless in 15 minutes and a medical record that must stay private for 30 years are completely different risks, even if both use the same algorithm.

27
00:02:54,375 --> 00:02:58,233
Next up: The hard part: finding crypto you forgot you had.

28
00:02:58,233 --> 00:03:00,733
The visible crypto is easy.

29
00:03:00,733 --> 00:03:03,040
The dangerous crypto is hidden.

30
00:03:03,040 --> 00:03:05,072
Hunt in all of these places:

31
00:03:05,072 --> 00:03:14,987
TLS everywhere — public endpoints, internal mTLS between services, database connections, message-broker TLS, VPNs..

32
00:03:14,987 --> 00:03:23,677
Tokens and signatures — JWT signing keys, API request signing, code/firmware signing, document signing..

33
00:03:23,677 --> 00:03:37,235
Data at rest — disk/volume encryption, encrypted database columns, encrypted backups and archives (these have the longest lifetimes — backups from today might be restored in 2040)..

34
00:03:37,235 --> 00:03:41,141
Dependencies — the crypto your libraries use internally.

35
00:03:41,141 --> 00:03:48,100
A package.json or requirements.txt doesn't show you that a transitive dependency pins an algorithm.

36
00:03:48,100 --> 00:03:51,117
This is where automated scanning earns its keep..

37
00:03:51,117 --> 00:03:57,776
Certificates and PKI — your CA hierarchy, cert algorithms, and key sizes..

38
00:03:57,776 --> 00:04:02,836
Secrets managers and HSMs — what algorithms they're configured for..

39
00:04:02,836 --> 00:04:18,281
Practical tactics: scan source for crypto API calls and hard-coded algorithm names, enumerate TLS configs across hosts, pull certificate inventories, and use SBOM/dependency tooling to surface library-level crypto.

40
00:04:18,281 --> 00:04:22,632
The goal of the first pass isn't perfection — it's to stop being blind.

41
00:04:22,632 --> 00:04:26,526
Let's explore Turn the inventory into a priority order.

42
00:04:26,526 --> 00:04:28,449
A raw list isn't a plan.

43
00:04:28,449 --> 00:04:29,218
Sort it.

44
00:04:29,218 --> 00:04:31,274
Rank each asset by roughly:

45
00:04:31,298 --> 00:04:40,118
Urgent: long-lived secrets crossing capturable networks — health, financial, legal, government data; long-retention backups.

46
00:04:40,118 --> 00:04:42,798
These are the harvest-now-decrypt-later targets.

47
00:04:42,798 --> 00:04:45,647
Migrate (in hybrid mode) first..

48
00:04:45,647 --> 00:04:50,502
Important: medium-lifetime data and broadly-exposed signing keys..

49
00:04:50,502 --> 00:04:57,401
Later: ephemeral data whose value evaporates quickly — short sessions, transient caches..

50
00:04:57,401 --> 00:05:00,250
This sorted list is your migration roadmap.

51
00:05:00,250 --> 00:05:04,505
You're not migrating "the company"; you're migrating the top of this list first.

52
00:05:04,505 --> 00:05:07,594
Now let's look at Note crypto-agility while you're in there.

53
00:05:07,594 --> 00:05:12,498
For each asset, record whether the algorithm is swappable or hard-coded.

54
00:05:12,498 --> 00:05:20,418
This does double duty: it tells you the effort to migrate each item, and it surfaces the architectural debt you need to pay down.

55
00:05:20,418 --> 00:05:29,998
Hard-coded crypto is what turns migration into a multi-quarter slog; flagging it now lets you prioritize adding an agility layer where it'll hurt most.

56
00:05:29,998 --> 00:05:31,921
Now, let's talk about Keep it alive.

57
00:05:31,921 --> 00:05:37,461
A CBOM is not a one-time spreadsheet — it's a living artifact, like an SBOM.

58
00:05:37,461 --> 00:05:41,572
New services add crypto; dependencies change algorithms.

59
00:05:41,572 --> 00:05:51,103
Wire inventory updates into your process: a CI check that flags new cryptographic dependencies, a periodic re-scan, and ownership so it doesn't rot.

60
00:05:51,103 --> 00:05:58,796
The teams that will swap algorithms calmly when the 2030 deprecation lands are the ones whose CBOM is current and trusted.

61
00:05:58,796 --> 00:06:00,418
Moving on to The takeaway.

62
00:06:00,418 --> 00:06:06,644
Building a Cryptographic Bill of Materials is the boring, decisive first step of post-quantum migration.

63
00:06:06,644 --> 00:06:17,774
Inventory every cryptographic use, hunt down the hidden ones (dependencies and backups especially), tag each with its data-confidentiality lifetime, and sort by risk.

64
00:06:17,774 --> 00:06:23,856
What falls out is a prioritized migration plan grounded in reality instead of guesswork.

65
00:06:23,856 --> 00:06:31,716
Start it in 2026 — before the deadlines force you to do it under pressure, and before you find the RSA you missed the hard way.

66
